        "body": "Long upon the mountains weary,\n<br>Have the scattered flocks been torn;\n<br>Dark the dessert paths, and dreary;\n<br>Grievous trials have they borne.\n<br>Now the gathering call is sounding,\n<br>Solemn in its warning voice;\n<br>Union, faith, and love, abounding,\n<br>Bid the little flock rejoice.\n<br>\n<br>Now the light of truth they're seeking,\n<br>In its onward track pursue;\n<br>All the ten commandments keeping,\n<br>They are holy, just, and true.\n<br>On the words of lire they're feeding,\n<br>Precious to their taste so sweet;\n<br>All their Master's percepts heeding,\n<br>Bowing humbly to His feet.\n<br>\n<br>In that world of light and beauty,\n<br>In that golden city fair,\n<br>Soon its pearly gates they'll enter,\n<br>And of all its glories share.\n<br>There, divine the soul's expansions;\n<br>Free from sin, and death, and pain;\n<br>Tear will never dim those mansions\n<br>Where the saints immortal reign.\n<br>\n<br>Soon He comes! With clouds descending;\n<br>All His saints, entombed arise;\n<br>The redeemed, in anthems blending,\n<br>Shout their victory through the skies.\n<br>O, we long for Thine appearing;\n<br>Come, O Savior, quickly come!\n<br>Blessed hope! Our spirits cheering,\n<br>Take thy ransomed children home."
